d in Sweden guaranteeing the right to use Sámi in dealing with the courts and government agencies, much damage had already been done to the Sámi languages, as many young people in Sámi communities cannot speak Sámi fluently. For Ume Sámi, there are only 10-20 remaining native speakers, and its EGIDS categorization is endangered (EGIDS 6b-9).%0a%3c Revitalization efforts for the Sámi languages are ongoing in Sweden. The government-funded Sámi Language Center, which recruited its staff from the speakers of different Sámi languages, has undertaken various revitalization projects. They started by researching the the different cultural and linguistic needs of the varied population of speakers of Sámi languages in Sweden. They have developed a language learning mentor program, which paired students with older native speakers of the Ume Sami language and encouraged them to meet regularly to use Ume Sámi while doing everyday activities, such as cooking. Additionally, the Language Block program aimed at removing mental and emotional blocks that prevented many Sámi who had acquired the language in childhood from speaking it in their daily lives. This consisted of group meetings for language exercises, along with homework between sessions. Though the Sámi languages may be endangered, there are active and ongoing efforts to increase their usage.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources%0a%3c Indigenous Peoples of the Arctic Council%0a%3c https://www.arcticpeoples.com/sagstallamin-the-saami-languages%0a%3c %0a%3c World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples%0a%3c https://minorityrights.org/minorities/sami-3/%0a%3c %0a%3c Ethnologue%0a%3c https://www.ethnologue.com/size-and-vitality/sju%0a%3c %0a%3c Overcoming Silence and Sorrow: Sami Language Revitalization in Sweden: %0a%3c https://repository.usfca.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1051&context=ijhre%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsen